\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The AI translation layer is genuinely viable now in a way it wasn't 3-4 years ago. Here's the real breakdown:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 What AI translation handles well:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 UI strings, buttons, navigation, labels \'97 near perfect\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 General explanatory text \'97 very good\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Your AI explanation layer is actually self-solving here \'97 if you prompt Claude/GPT to respond in the user's preferred language, the health record explanations localize automatically with no extra work\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Where AI translation falls short for a health app specifically:
\f1\b0 \
Medical terminology is the critical gap. Clinical terms have specific translations that vary by country \'97 not just language. A German cardiologist and an Austrian cardiologist may use different terms for the same condition. AI gets this right maybe 85-90% of the time, and in healthcare that 10-15% error rate is a real liability, both legally and reputationally.\
Japan is the hardest case. Medical Japanese uses a complex mix of kanji, specialized terminology borrowed from German (historically Japanese medicine was German-influenced), and honorific language conventions for patient-facing communication. AI translation into Japanese medical context is functional but not polished enough to feel native.\

\f0\b The practical tooling answer:
\f1\b0 \
SwiftUI's localization is well-architected \'97 you'd use 
\f3\fs26 .strings
\f1\fs24  files and 
\f3\fs26 LocalizedStringKey
\f1\fs24  throughout the app. The structure would be:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Extract all UI strings into localization files \'97 one sprint\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Run AI translation as a first pass \'97 fast and cheap\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 For medical content specifically, a native-speaking medical reviewer does a pass \'97 this is where you'd bring in a specialist, but only for the medical terminology layer, not the entire app\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Cost reality for Japan:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AI first pass: essentially free\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Medical terminology review by a Japanese medical translator: $2-5k one-time\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Ongoing: any new medical terms added get the same review\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Cost reality for European languages (German, French, Spanish, Italian):
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 AI first pass: free\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Medical review: $1-3k per language\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Much lower risk than Japanese due to medical terminology being more standardized across Latin-based languages\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 The bigger question than translation quality
\f1\b0  is actually regulatory. Japan has the PMDA (pharmaceutical and medical device agency) with specific rules around health information apps. Germany has the DiGA framework \'97 apps that make health claims can be classified as medical devices requiring certification. France's CNIL adds GDPR-plus requirements.\

\f0\b Bottom line recommendation:
\f1\b0 \
For UK/Canada/Australia \'97 no translation needed, ship immediately.\
For European markets \'97 AI translation gets you 90% there, a $1-3k medical reviewer per language gets you to production quality. Structurally easy to add to the app in one sprint.\
For Japan \'97 technically achievable with AI plus a specialist reviewer, but the regulatory environment warrants research before investing in localization. The market opportunity is real but the compliance surface is different.\
The actual code work to support multiple languages in SwiftUI is straightforward and worth doing early even if you only launch in English \'97 it sets up the infrastructure so adding languages later is additive rather than architectural.\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

