\cf0 That's actually the more prudent approach and shows good product thinking. A few considerations:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 The case for delisting specific countries:
\f1\b0 \
A health app with inaccurate medical translations isn't just a bad user experience \'97 it's a potential liability. If a Japanese user misunderstands a health record explanation because of a poor translation, that's a different category of problem than a food delivery app getting something wrong.\
Regulatory exposure is real. Launching in Germany without understanding the DiGA framework, or Japan without PMDA consideration, and then having to pull the app later is messier than never launching there in the first place.\
App Store reputation is global. A 2-star review in Japanese saying "translations are wrong and dangerous" affects your overall rating.\

\f0\b How to do it in App Store Connect:
\f1\b0 \
It's straightforward \'97 under your app's pricing and availability settings you can toggle individual countries on and off. You'd keep it live in US, UK, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Ireland, Singapore (all English-language, low regulatory friction) and delist everywhere else until you're ready.\

\f0\b The nuanced middle ground:
\f1\b0 \
Some countries have meaningful English-speaking expat populations who would use an English-language health app without needing localization \'97 UAE, Netherlands, Scandinavia. Worth keeping those live even before localization since English proficiency is high and regulatory risk for an English-language app serving English speakers is lower.\

